/* CISSP :: content/quiz3.js — CISSP Domain 3 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISSP = window.CISSP || {}; CISSP.questions = CISSP.questions || [];
CISSP.questions.push(
  {"id":"D3-001","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"easy","q":"A security architect is designing a new application and wants every access request evaluated on its own merits regardless of network location. Which principle BEST describes this approach?","options":["Zero trust ('never trust, always verify')","Implicit trust for the internal LAN","Security through obscurity","Perimeter-only defense"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Zero trust ('never trust, always verify')</strong> removes implicit trust based on network location and evaluates every request against identity, device, and context.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Implicit trust for the internal LAN</b>: trusting anything already inside the perimeter is exactly what zero trust rejects.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security through obscurity</b>: hiding design details is not a trust model and is discouraged as a primary control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Perimeter-only defense</b>: a hard shell with a soft interior fails once an attacker is inside, the weakness zero trust addresses.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-002","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"easy","q":"During design review, an engineer proposes granting a batch service account broad database rights 'to avoid future permission tickets.' Which secure design principle should the reviewer cite to push back?","options":["Open design","Least privilege","Fail-open defaults","Economy of mechanism"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Least privilege</strong> requires each subject to hold only the access needed for its function, so a service account should get narrowly scoped rights, not broad ones for convenience.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Open design</b>: open design concerns not relying on secrecy of the mechanism, not scoping account rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail-open defaults</b>: failing open is generally insecure; it does not justify broad rights and is not the principle at issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>Economy of mechanism</b>: economy of mechanism favors simple designs, which is unrelated to over-provisioning a single account.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-003","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"medium","q":"A wire-transfer workflow is being designed so that no single employee can both create and approve a payment. Which principle is being applied?","options":["Defense in depth","Single point of failure","Separation of duties","Fail-secure"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Separation of duties</strong> splits a sensitive task across multiple people so collusion is required to commit fraud, exactly the create-versus-approve split described.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth</b>: defense in depth layers multiple controls, but it does not specifically split a task between people.</span><span class='qd'><b>Single point of failure</b>: this is a reliability weakness, not a control being applied.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail-secure</b>: fail-secure describes what a control does on failure, not the division of a transaction.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-004","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"easy","q":"An organization layers a firewall, network segmentation, host hardening, and user training so that a failure in one control is compensated by others. This strategy is BEST called:","options":["Least privilege","Trust but verify","Security through obscurity","Defense in depth"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Defense in depth</strong> stacks diverse, overlapping controls so no single failure exposes the asset.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: least privilege limits access rights; it is not about layering multiple controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security through obscurity</b>: obscurity hides details and is not a layered-defense strategy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trust but verify</b>: this slogan predates and is weaker than the layered control concept described.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-005","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"easy","q":"A designer wants sensitive functions to remain protected even if an attacker fully understands the system's internal logic, relying instead on secret keys. Which principle supports this?","options":["Open design (Kerckhoffs's principle)","Security through obscurity","Implicit trust","Fail-open"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Open design (Kerckhoffs's principle)</strong> holds that security should depend on protected keys, not on secrecy of the design, so the system stays secure even if its internals are known.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Security through obscurity</b>: this is the opposite—relying on hiding the design—which open design explicitly rejects.</span><span class='qd'><b>Implicit trust</b>: implicit trust is a trust-model concept unrelated to whether design secrecy protects the system.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail-open</b>: fail-open describes failure behavior, not reliance on keys versus secrecy.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-006","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"medium","q":"A high-security data center door controller must decide what to do if it loses power. Which failure mode BEST preserves confidentiality of the protected room?","options":["Fail-open so people can exit freely","Fail-secure (fail-closed) so the door stays locked","Fail into maintenance mode with no logging","Fail to a default administrative password"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Fail-secure (fail-closed) so the door stays locked</strong> preserves confidentiality by denying access when the control fails; life-safety codes are handled separately with mechanical egress.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail-open so people can exit freely</b>: fail-open favors availability/safety but leaves the room accessible, harming confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail into maintenance mode with no logging</b>: losing logging during failure removes accountability and does not protect the room.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail to a default administrative password</b>: reverting to a known credential is a severe vulnerability, not a protective failure mode.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-007","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"medium","q":"An architect is asked to simplify a security subsystem that has grown complex, arguing that a smaller trusted computing base is easier to verify. Which design principle is invoked?","options":["Defense in depth","Complete mediation","Economy of mechanism","Separation of duties"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Economy of mechanism</strong> favors keeping security-critical designs as small and simple as possible so they can be analyzed and trusted.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Complete mediation</b>: complete mediation means checking every access, not reducing complexity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth</b>: defense in depth adds layers, which can increase, not reduce, complexity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Separation of duties</b>: this splits responsibilities among people and is unrelated to subsystem simplicity.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-008","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"hard","q":"A cached authorization decision lets a user keep access to a file after their permission was revoked mid-session. Which secure design principle was violated?","options":["Least common mechanism","Open design","Psychological acceptability","Complete mediation"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Complete mediation</strong> requires that every access to an object be checked against current authorization, so relying on a stale cached decision violates it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least common mechanism</b>: this concerns minimizing shared mechanisms among users, not re-checking each access.</span><span class='qd'><b>Psychological acceptability</b>: this addresses usability of controls, not authorization freshness.</span><span class='qd'><b>Open design</b>: open design concerns secrecy of the mechanism, not per-access checking.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-009","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"easy","q":"A zero-trust architecture relies on a component that evaluates policy and issues an allow/deny decision for each request. In the NIST SP 800-207 model this is the:","options":["Policy Decision Point (PDP)","Policy Enforcement Point (PEP)","Certificate authority","Load balancer"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Policy Decision Point (PDP)</strong> evaluates policy and context to grant or deny access; the PEP then enforces that decision at the resource.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Policy Enforcement Point (PEP)</b>: the PEP enforces the decision but does not make it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificate authority</b>: a CA issues certificates and is not the zero-trust decision engine.</span><span class='qd'><b>Load balancer</b>: a load balancer distributes traffic and makes no access-control decisions.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-010","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"easy","q":"A team is building 'privacy by design' into a new customer platform. Which action BEST reflects that principle at the design stage?","options":["Collecting all possible data now in case it is useful later","Minimizing data collection and embedding privacy controls from the outset","Adding a privacy notice only after launch","Storing data indefinitely to simplify retention"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Minimizing data collection and embedding privacy controls from the outset</strong> is the essence of privacy by design—data minimization and proactive controls built in, not bolted on.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Collecting all possible data now in case it is useful later</b>: over-collection is the opposite of data minimization.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding a privacy notice only after launch</b>: bolting privacy on afterward contradicts 'by design.'</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing data indefinitely to simplify retention</b>: indefinite retention increases exposure and violates minimization.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-011","domain":3,"obj":"3.1","diff":"hard","q":"A CISO wants a design where compromise of one microservice does not automatically grant access to others, keeping trust boundaries tight. Which combination BEST achieves this?","options":["A single shared admin credential across services","One flat network with host firewalls disabled","Microsegmentation with per-service identity and least privilege","Broad service accounts to reduce ticket volume"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Microsegmentation with per-service identity and least privilege</strong> confines a compromised service and prevents lateral movement, aligning with zero-trust segmentation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single shared admin credential across services</b>: a shared credential means one compromise unlocks everything.</span><span class='qd'><b>One flat network with host firewalls disabled</b>: a flat, open network enables lateral movement, the opposite of containment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Broad service accounts to reduce ticket volume</b>: broad accounts violate least privilege and widen blast radius.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-012","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"medium","q":"Under the Bell-LaPadula model, a subject cleared at Secret is prevented from reading Top Secret data. Which property enforces this?","options":["The Discretionary Security Property","The *-property (no write down)","The Strong Star Property","The Simple Security Property (no read up)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The Simple Security Property (no read up)</strong> stops a subject from reading data classified above its clearance, protecting confidentiality.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The *-property (no write down)</b>: the star property prevents writing to a lower level, not reading up.</span><span class='qd'><b>The Strong Star Property</b>: this restricts reads and writes to the same level and is not the rule blocking read-up specifically.</span><span class='qd'><b>The Discretionary Security Property</b>: this governs discretionary access-matrix permissions, not the mandatory no-read-up rule.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-013","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"easy","q":"Bell-LaPadula's *-property forbids a Top Secret user from writing into a Confidential document. What is the security goal of this 'no write down' rule?","options":["Preventing high-classification data from leaking to a lower level","Ensuring data integrity against unauthorized modification","Guaranteeing availability of the document","Enforcing separation of duties"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Preventing high-classification data from leaking to a lower level</strong> is the confidentiality goal of no-write-down, blocking downgrade of sensitive content.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ensuring data integrity against unauthorized modification</b>: Bell-LaPadula addresses confidentiality, not integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Guaranteeing availability of the document</b>: the model says nothing about availability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enforcing separation of duties</b>: separation of duties is an operational control, not a BLP property.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-014","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"hard","q":"An integrity-focused system must stop a low-integrity process from corrupting high-integrity data. Which Biba property enforces 'no write up'?","options":["The Simple Integrity Property","The * (Star) Integrity Property","The Simple Security Property","The Discretionary Security Property"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The * (Star) Integrity Property</strong> enforces 'no write up,' preventing a lower-integrity subject from writing to a higher-integrity object.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The Simple Integrity Property</b>: the simple integrity property is 'no read down,' not no write up.</span><span class='qd'><b>The Simple Security Property</b>: that is a Bell-LaPadula confidentiality rule, not a Biba integrity rule.</span><span class='qd'><b>The Discretionary Security Property</b>: this is a discretionary access rule, unrelated to Biba's mandatory integrity properties.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-015","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"medium","q":"Biba's Simple Integrity Property states that a subject may not read data at a lower integrity level. What risk does 'no read down' mitigate?","options":["Denial of service against the object","Confidential data being read by an uncleared subject","A trusted process being contaminated by unreliable, lower-integrity input","Weak password reuse"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A trusted process being contaminated by unreliable, lower-integrity input</strong> is exactly what no-read-down prevents, protecting the integrity of high-integrity subjects.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidential data being read by an uncleared subject</b>: that is a confidentiality concern handled by Bell-LaPadula.</span><span class='qd'><b>Denial of service against the object</b>: Biba does not address availability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Weak password reuse</b>: authentication hygiene is outside the Biba model.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-016","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"hard","q":"A designer needs an integrity model that ties users to programs and programs to data, enforcing well-formed transactions and separation of duties for commercial systems. Which model fits BEST?","options":["Bell-LaPadula","Graham-Denning","Take-Grant","Clark-Wilson"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Clark-Wilson</strong> enforces integrity through well-formed transactions and the access-control triple (user, transformation procedure, constrained data item), with duties separated—ideal for commercial integrity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Bell-LaPadula</b>: BLP protects confidentiality, not commercial integrity via transactions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Take-Grant</b>: Take-Grant analyzes how rights propagate, not well-formed transactions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Graham-Denning</b>: Graham-Denning defines primitive rights operations, not the transaction-integrity framework described.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-017","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"easy","q":"In Clark-Wilson terminology, the only way a user may modify protected data is through a certified program that transforms data from one valid state to another. What is this program called?","options":["A transformation procedure (TP)","A constrained data item (CDI)","An unconstrained data item (UDI)","An integrity verification procedure (IVP)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A transformation procedure (TP)</strong> is the certified program that performs well-formed transactions, the only path to change constrained data items.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A constrained data item (CDI)</b>: a CDI is the protected data itself, not the program that changes it.</span><span class='qd'><b>An unconstrained data item (UDI)</b>: a UDI is data outside integrity control, such as raw input.</span><span class='qd'><b>An integrity verification procedure (IVP)</b>: an IVP checks that CDIs are in a valid state; it does not perform the transactions.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-018","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"medium","q":"Two competing clients hire the same consulting firm, and the firm must prevent an analyst who accessed Client A's data from accessing Client B's. Which model addresses this conflict of interest?","options":["Biba","Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall)","Lattice-based confidentiality","Bell-LaPadula"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall)</strong> dynamically restricts access based on prior accesses to prevent conflicts of interest between competing clients.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Biba</b>: Biba governs integrity levels, not conflict-of-interest walls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Lattice-based confidentiality</b>: a lattice orders sensitivity levels but does not encode dynamic conflict classes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Bell-LaPadula</b>: BLP enforces static clearance-based confidentiality, not access history-based separation.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-019","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"easy","q":"Bell-LaPadula and Biba both organize subjects and objects into ordered security levels with dominance relationships. This underlying mathematical structure is called a:","options":["State machine","Finite automaton","Lattice","Reference monitor"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Lattice</strong> is the partially ordered structure of security levels with defined dominance, underpinning both Bell-LaPadula and Biba.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>State machine</b>: a state machine models transitions between secure states, a related but distinct concept.</span><span class='qd'><b>Finite automaton</b>: an automaton is a computation model, not the ordering of security levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reference monitor</b>: a reference monitor mediates access; it is not the ordering structure itself.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-020","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"medium","q":"A model is described as always transitioning from one secure state to another such that if it begins secure it remains secure across any operation. This describes a:","options":["Noninterference model","Access matrix model","Information flow model","State machine (secure state) model"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>State machine (secure state) model</strong> proves that every valid transition from a secure state yields another secure state, so the system is always secure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Noninterference model</b>: noninterference focuses on high-level actions not affecting low-level outputs, a different guarantee.</span><span class='qd'><b>Information flow model</b>: information flow tracks data movement between levels, not the secure-state transition property.</span><span class='qd'><b>Access matrix model</b>: the access matrix lists subject/object rights and is not a transition-security proof.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-021","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"medium","q":"A model ensures that actions taken by high-security subjects produce no observable effect on what low-security subjects can see, blocking covert signaling between levels. This is the:","options":["Noninterference model","Brewer-Nash model","Clark-Wilson model","Take-Grant model"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Noninterference model</strong> guarantees that high-level activity does not interfere with low-level observations, mitigating covert channels between levels.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Brewer-Nash model</b>: Brewer-Nash handles conflict-of-interest separation, not interference between levels.</span><span class='qd'><b>Clark-Wilson model</b>: Clark-Wilson enforces transaction integrity, not observational noninterference.</span><span class='qd'><b>Take-Grant model</b>: Take-Grant models rights propagation, unrelated to covert signaling.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-022","domain":3,"obj":"3.2","diff":"medium","q":"An auditor asks which Bell-LaPadula rule would allow a Secret subject to write into a Top Secret file. Which statement is correct?","options":["The Simple Security Property permits it","The *-property permits write up to a higher level","No BLP rule permits reading up","Writing up is always forbidden in BLP"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The *-property permits write up to a higher level</strong> because BLP forbids write-down to protect confidentiality, so writing upward is allowed by the star property.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The Simple Security Property permits it</b>: the simple security property governs reads (no read up), not writes.</span><span class='qd'><b>No BLP rule permits reading up</b>: true but irrelevant—the question asks about writing up, not reading up.</span><span class='qd'><b>Writing up is always forbidden in BLP</b>: BLP permits write-up; it is write-down that is forbidden.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-023","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"easy","q":"A government agency will only procure a product whose security has been independently evaluated against a defined Protection Profile and Security Target. Which framework provides this?","options":["COBIT","PCI DSS","Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)","OWASP ASVS"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)</strong> evaluates products against Protection Profiles and Security Targets and assigns an assurance level, supporting procurement decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>PCI DSS</b>: PCI DSS is a payment-card security standard, not a product-evaluation framework.</span><span class='qd'><b>COBIT</b>: COBIT is an IT governance framework, not a product certification scheme.</span><span class='qd'><b>OWASP ASVS</b>: ASVS is an application-security verification standard, not the CC evaluation regime.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-024","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"medium","q":"In Common Criteria, the document that states the security requirements and claims for the specific product being evaluated (the TOE) is the:","options":["Protection Profile (PP)","Trusted Computing Base (TCB)","Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL)","Security Target (ST)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Security Target (ST)</strong> describes the specific Target of Evaluation and the security claims being evaluated for that product.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Protection Profile (PP)</b>: a PP states generic requirements for a class of products, not the specific product's claims.</span><span class='qd'><b>Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL)</b>: the EAL is the rigor rating, not the requirements document.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusted Computing Base (TCB)</b>: the TCB is the set of trusted components, not a CC document.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-025","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"medium","q":"A vendor advertises an 'EAL5' product. What does a higher Evaluation Assurance Level primarily indicate?","options":["Greater depth and rigor of the security evaluation, not necessarily stronger security","The product has more features than lower-EAL products","The product is unbreakable","Compliance with GDPR"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Greater depth and rigor of the security evaluation, not necessarily stronger security</strong> is what a higher EAL means—more thorough testing and documentation, which does not guarantee superior real-world security.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The product has more features than lower-EAL products</b>: EAL measures assurance depth, not feature count.</span><span class='qd'><b>The product is unbreakable</b>: no evaluation makes a product unbreakable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compliance with GDPR</b>: EAL is a technical assurance rating, unrelated to a privacy regulation.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-026","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"easy","q":"A Common Criteria Protection Profile is BEST described as:","options":["A customer's implementation-specific claims for one product","An implementation-independent set of security requirements for a category of products","A cryptographic key exchange protocol","A list of a company's assets"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An implementation-independent set of security requirements for a category of products</strong> defines what a Protection Profile is—reusable requirements a class of products must meet.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A customer's implementation-specific claims for one product</b>: that describes a Security Target, not a Protection Profile.</span><span class='qd'><b>A cryptographic key exchange protocol</b>: a PP is a requirements document, not a protocol.</span><span class='qd'><b>A list of a company's assets</b>: an asset inventory is unrelated to CC Protection Profiles.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-027","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"medium","q":"During system authorization, an assessor validates that implemented controls actually work, and an authorizing official then formally accepts residual risk before go-live. In NIST RMF terms these steps are:","options":["Categorize and select","Monitor and disposal","Assess and authorize","Implement and categorize"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Assess and authorize</strong> are the RMF steps where controls are tested (assess) and an authorizing official accepts residual risk and grants an ATO (authorize).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Categorize and select</b>: those earlier steps set impact level and choose controls, not validation and acceptance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Monitor and disposal</b>: monitoring follows authorization; disposal is end-of-life, neither is the validate-and-accept pair.</span><span class='qd'><b>Implement and categorize</b>: implementing installs controls and categorization is the first step—neither validates or accepts risk.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-028","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is choosing between a formal certification of a product and the accreditation of a whole system. Which statement BEST distinguishes them?","options":["Certification is management's acceptance of risk; accreditation is the technical evaluation","Accreditation is performed only by vendors","They are identical terms","Certification is the technical evaluation of controls; accreditation is management's formal acceptance to operate"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Certification is the technical evaluation of controls; accreditation is management's formal acceptance to operate</strong> correctly separates the technical assessment from the management authorization decision.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Certification is management's acceptance of risk; accreditation is the technical evaluation</b>: this reverses the two definitions.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are identical terms</b>: they are distinct phases with different owners.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accreditation is performed only by vendors</b>: accreditation is a management/authorizing-official decision, not a vendor task.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-029","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"medium","q":"A control framework maps organizational security requirements to specific safeguards and their assessment procedures for U.S. federal systems. Which catalog is MOST relevant?","options":["NIST SP 800-53","ISO 9001","ITIL","FIPS 197"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>NIST SP 800-53</strong> is the federal control catalog listing safeguards and, with 800-53A, their assessment procedures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>ISO 9001</b>: ISO 9001 addresses quality management, not security controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>ITIL</b>: ITIL covers IT service management processes, not a control catalog.</span><span class='qd'><b>FIPS 197</b>: FIPS 197 specifies the AES algorithm, not a control framework.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-030","domain":3,"obj":"3.3","diff":"easy","q":"A control that discourages a would-be attacker by signaling that violations will be detected and punished (such as warning banners and visible cameras) is classified as:","options":["A corrective control","A deterrent control","A recovery control","A compensating control"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A deterrent control</strong> aims to dissuade a potential attacker before an act occurs, as with warning banners and visible surveillance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A corrective control</b>: corrective controls fix or restore after an incident, not dissuade beforehand.</span><span class='qd'><b>A recovery control</b>: recovery controls restore operations, not deter.</span><span class='qd'><b>A compensating control</b>: a compensating control substitutes for an infeasible primary control; it is a role, not the deterrent function described.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-031","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"medium","q":"A laptop needs a hardware component that securely stores platform measurements and binds disk-encryption keys to the boot state. Which component is designed for this?","options":["A smart card reader","A hardware security module (HSM) appliance","A Trusted Platform Module (TPM)","A network TAP"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A Trusted Platform Module (TPM)</strong> stores platform configuration measurements in PCRs and can seal disk-encryption keys so they release only in a known-good boot state.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A hardware security module (HSM) appliance</b>: an HSM protects keys at scale for servers/CAs, not per-laptop boot binding.</span><span class='qd'><b>A smart card reader</b>: a reader interfaces a user token; it does not measure boot state.</span><span class='qd'><b>A network TAP</b>: a TAP captures traffic and has no key-sealing role.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-032","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"easy","q":"A certificate authority must generate and protect its private signing keys inside tamper-resistant hardware that never exposes the key in plaintext. Which device is MOST appropriate?","options":["A TPM soldered to a workstation","A software keystore file","A USB flash drive","A hardware security module (HSM)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A hardware security module (HSM)</strong> is purpose-built to generate, store, and use CA private keys in tamper-resistant hardware without exposing plaintext keys.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A TPM soldered to a workstation</b>: a TPM secures a single platform's keys, not enterprise CA key operations at scale.</span><span class='qd'><b>A USB flash drive</b>: a flash drive offers no tamper resistance or protected cryptographic processing.</span><span class='qd'><b>A software keystore file</b>: a software keystore exposes keys to the host OS and memory, defeating the requirement.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-033","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"hard","q":"A security model requires a component that mediates ALL access between subjects and objects, is tamperproof, and is small enough to be fully tested. This abstract concept is the:","options":["Reference monitor","Security kernel","Trusted computing base","Protection ring 3"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Reference monitor</strong> is the abstract concept that must mediate every access, be tamperproof, and be verifiable (small enough to test).<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Security kernel</b>: the security kernel is the actual implementation of the reference monitor, not the abstract concept.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusted computing base</b>: the TCB is the totality of protection mechanisms, broader than the reference monitor.</span><span class='qd'><b>Protection ring 3</b>: ring 3 is the least-privileged user ring, not an access-mediation concept.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-034","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"medium","q":"The complete set of hardware, firmware, and software responsible for enforcing a system's security policy is called the:","options":["Reference monitor","Trusted Computing Base (TCB)","Security perimeter's DMZ","Hypervisor"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Trusted Computing Base (TCB)</strong> is the totality of protection mechanisms whose correct operation is essential to enforcing the security policy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Reference monitor</b>: the reference monitor is a concept within the TCB, not the whole set of mechanisms.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security perimeter's DMZ</b>: a DMZ is a network zone, not the trusted enforcement set.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hypervisor</b>: a hypervisor may be part of a TCB but is not, by itself, the definition.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-035","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"easy","q":"A CPU uses privilege levels so that user applications cannot directly execute sensitive hardware instructions reserved for the operating system. This protection scheme is known as:","options":["Trusted path","Address space layout randomization","Protection rings","Data execution prevention"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Protection rings</strong> layer privilege (ring 0 kernel to ring 3 user) so untrusted code cannot execute privileged instructions directly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Address space layout randomization</b>: ASLR randomizes memory layout to hinder exploits, not partition CPU privilege.</span><span class='qd'><b>Trusted path</b>: a trusted path is a protected communication channel to the TCB, not CPU privilege layering.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data execution prevention</b>: DEP marks memory non-executable; it is not the ring-privilege scheme.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-036","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"medium","q":"To defeat firmware-level rootkits, a laptop verifies each boot-stage signature against a trusted key before execution. This capability is BEST described as:","options":["A password-protected screensaver","Full-disk encryption","A host-based firewall","Secure/measured boot with a hardware root of trust"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Secure/measured boot with a hardware root of trust</strong> validates each stage's signature/measurement from a trusted anchor, blocking tampered firmware before it runs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption</b>: FDE protects data at rest but does not verify boot-stage integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>A host-based firewall</b>: a firewall filters network traffic and does not validate firmware.</span><span class='qd'><b>A password-protected screensaver</b>: a screensaver lock does nothing against boot-level rootkits.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-037","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"medium","q":"A trusted path is provided so a user can be certain they are communicating directly with the security kernel, not a spoofed prompt. What attack does this MOST directly counter?","options":["A Trojan login screen harvesting credentials","A SQL injection against the database","A distributed denial-of-service flood","A physical tailgating attempt"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A Trojan login screen harvesting credentials</strong> is what a trusted path defends against, assuring the user the prompt is genuine and not spoofed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A SQL injection against the database</b>: injection is an input-validation issue unrelated to trusted-path assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>A distributed denial-of-service flood</b>: DDoS is an availability attack, not a spoofed-interface attack.</span><span class='qd'><b>A physical tailgating attempt</b>: tailgating is a facility-access issue, not a trusted-path concern.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-038","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"easy","q":"Which statement BEST describes the security kernel?","options":["The abstract policy defining allowed accesses","The hardware, firmware, and software that implement the reference monitor concept","The list of all users on a system","A backup copy of the operating system"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The hardware, firmware, and software that implement the reference monitor concept</strong> is the definition of the security kernel—the concrete realization of the reference monitor.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The abstract policy defining allowed accesses</b>: that is closer to a security policy or the reference-monitor concept, not the kernel implementation.</span><span class='qd'><b>The list of all users on a system</b>: a user list is not a protection mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>A backup copy of the operating system</b>: a backup is not the enforcement component.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-039","domain":3,"obj":"3.4","diff":"hard","q":"An architect wants to run sensitive code in an isolated, hardware-enforced region that even a compromised operating system cannot read. Which capability provides this?","options":["A DMZ subnet","A standard virtual machine","A trusted execution environment (TEE)/secure enclave","A RAID array"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A trusted execution environment (TEE)/secure enclave</strong> isolates code and data in hardware so even a privileged, compromised OS cannot inspect it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A standard virtual machine</b>: a normal VM is still visible to the hypervisor and does not resist a compromised host OS the way a TEE does.</span><span class='qd'><b>A DMZ subnet</b>: a DMZ isolates network exposure, not in-memory code from the OS.</span><span class='qd'><b>A RAID array</b>: RAID provides disk redundancy, not execution isolation.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-040","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"easy","q":"In an IaaS cloud deployment, a customer wonders who is responsible for patching the guest operating system. Under the shared responsibility model, the answer is:","options":["The cloud provider handles all patching","A third-party auditor patches it","Neither party is responsible","The customer patches the guest OS and applications; the provider secures the underlying infrastructure"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The customer patches the guest OS and applications; the provider secures the underlying infrastructure</strong> reflects IaaS shared responsibility—the customer owns the OS layer upward.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The cloud provider handles all patching</b>: in IaaS the provider does not patch the customer's guest OS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Neither party is responsible</b>: responsibility is always allocated, never nobody's.</span><span class='qd'><b>A third-party auditor patches it</b>: auditors assess controls; they do not operate patching.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-041","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"hard","q":"A tenant in a public cloud is concerned that a flaw in the hypervisor could let a malicious VM read another tenant's memory. This class of threat is BEST called:","options":["VM escape / hypervisor breakout","Cross-site scripting","ARP spoofing","Session fixation"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>VM escape / hypervisor breakout</strong> is when code breaks out of a guest VM to the hypervisor or other guests, threatening multi-tenant isolation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cross-site scripting</b>: XSS is a web-application injection flaw, not a virtualization isolation break.</span><span class='qd'><b>ARP spoofing</b>: ARP spoofing is a LAN man-in-the-middle technique, unrelated to hypervisor isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Session fixation</b>: session fixation attacks web sessions, not VM boundaries.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-042","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"medium","q":"An industrial plant runs legacy SCADA controllers that cannot be patched and were never designed for internet exposure. What is the MOST effective architectural mitigation?","options":["Expose them directly for easier remote management","Network segmentation/isolation with strict monitored gateways","Install consumer antivirus on the PLCs","Assign them public IP addresses"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Network segmentation/isolation with strict monitored gateways</strong> compensates for unpatchable ICS/SCADA devices by limiting exposure and controlling all traffic in and out.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Expose them directly for easier remote management</b>: direct exposure of fragile OT devices dramatically increases risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Install consumer antivirus on the PLCs</b>: PLCs typically cannot run standard AV and it does not address exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Assign them public IP addresses</b>: putting OT on public IPs invites attack, the opposite of isolation.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-043","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"medium","q":"A fleet of consumer IoT sensors ships with hard-coded default passwords and no update mechanism. Which characteristic makes them a persistent security concern?","options":["They are too expensive to deploy","They cannot connect to networks","They often lack patchability and secure defaults, remaining vulnerable for their lifespan","They use too much encryption"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>They often lack patchability and secure defaults, remaining vulnerable for their lifespan</strong> captures the core IoT risk—weak defaults and no updates leave devices exploitable long-term.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>They are too expensive to deploy</b>: cost is not the security characteristic in question.</span><span class='qd'><b>They cannot connect to networks</b>: IoT devices connect readily; that connectivity is part of the risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>They use too much encryption</b>: the problem is usually too little security, not too much.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-044","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"hard","q":"A company adopts serverless functions and worries about the security of shared execution infrastructure it does not control. Which concern is MOST specific to serverless?","options":["Increased responsibility for physical data-center security","Managing the hypervisor directly","The need to patch bare-metal servers","Reduced visibility and control over the underlying runtime, shifting focus to code, permissions, and dependencies"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Reduced visibility and control over the underlying runtime, shifting focus to code, permissions, and dependencies</strong> is the serverless-specific concern—the provider owns the platform, so the tenant secures function code, IAM roles, and libraries.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Increased responsibility for physical data-center security</b>: serverless reduces, not increases, tenant physical responsibility.</span><span class='qd'><b>The need to patch bare-metal servers</b>: there are no tenant-managed servers in serverless.</span><span class='qd'><b>Managing the hypervisor directly</b>: the tenant never touches the hypervisor in serverless.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-045","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which cloud model gives the customer the MOST control over the operating system and installed software?","options":["Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","Platform as a Service (PaaS)","Software as a Service (SaaS)","Function as a Service (FaaS)"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)</strong> gives the customer control over the guest OS, middleware, and applications, more than PaaS, SaaS, or FaaS.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Software as a Service (SaaS)</b>: SaaS gives the least control—only application configuration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Platform as a Service (PaaS)</b>: PaaS abstracts the OS, so the customer controls less than in IaaS.</span><span class='qd'><b>Function as a Service (FaaS)</b>: FaaS abstracts even the runtime, leaving only code control.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-046","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"medium","q":"An architect must avoid a design where all containers share the host kernel with no additional isolation for a high-risk workload. Which mitigation BEST strengthens container isolation?","options":["Running every container as root for simplicity","Using dedicated nodes, seccomp/AppArmor profiles, and non-root users, or a sandboxed runtime","Disabling all logging","Giving each container the host network namespace"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Using dedicated nodes, seccomp/AppArmor profiles, and non-root users, or a sandboxed runtime</strong> hardens container isolation despite the shared kernel by constraining syscalls, privileges, and tenancy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Running every container as root for simplicity</b>: root containers widen the blast radius of a breakout.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all logging</b>: removing logging reduces detection, not isolation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Giving each container the host network namespace</b>: sharing the host network removes network isolation entirely.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-047","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"easy","q":"A CISO is evaluating an on-premises database exposed only inside a segmented internal VLAN versus one reachable from the flat corporate network. Which architectural weakness does the flat network represent?","options":["Excessive encryption overhead","Too many firewall rules","Lack of segmentation enabling easy lateral movement","Overly strict least privilege"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Lack of segmentation enabling easy lateral movement</strong> is the weakness of a flat network—one compromised host can reach the database and everything else.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Excessive encryption overhead</b>: encryption overhead is a performance matter, not the segmentation flaw.</span><span class='qd'><b>Too many firewall rules</b>: a flat network typically has too few controls, not too many.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overly strict least privilege</b>: least privilege is desirable; it is not the weakness here.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-048","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"hard","q":"A distributed system uses many small services communicating over the network, and an attacker exploits an unauthenticated internal service to move laterally. Which design change BEST addresses this microservices weakness?","options":["Trust all internal traffic implicitly","Remove all API gateways","Combine all services into one monolith without controls","Enforce mutual TLS and service-to-service authorization (zero trust between services)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Enforce mutual TLS and service-to-service authorization (zero trust between services)</strong> authenticates and authorizes every internal call, blocking lateral movement between microservices.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Trust all internal traffic implicitly</b>: implicit internal trust is precisely what enabled the lateral movement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Combine all services into one monolith without controls</b>: merging services without controls does not add authentication and creates other issues.</span><span class='qd'><b>Remove all API gateways</b>: gateways add control points; removing them reduces security.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-049","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"medium","q":"An embedded medical device uses a general-purpose real-time OS but has limited memory and cannot run modern endpoint agents. Which compensating strategy is MOST appropriate?","options":["Wrap it with network controls, monitoring, and strict access restrictions around the device","Ignore it because it is embedded","Install a heavyweight EDR agent anyway","Connect it directly to the internet"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Wrap it with network controls, monitoring, and strict access restrictions around the device</strong> compensates for a constrained embedded system that cannot host security agents.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it because it is embedded</b>: ignoring a networked medical device leaves patients and data at risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Install a heavyweight EDR agent anyway</b>: the device lacks resources, so the agent cannot run reliably.</span><span class='qd'><b>Connect it directly to the internet</b>: direct exposure of a fragile device increases risk.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-050","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"medium","q":"A large-memory database server suffers a fault where the same physical RAM is exposed to two processes, leaking data between them. Which class of architecture vulnerability is this?","options":["A cross-site request forgery","A memory reuse / object reuse flaw","A phishing weakness","A weak password policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A memory reuse / object reuse flaw</strong> occurs when residual data in reused memory (or storage) is exposed to another process without being cleared.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A cross-site request forgery</b>: CSRF is a web session attack, not a memory-reuse issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>A phishing weakness</b>: phishing is social engineering, not an architecture memory flaw.</span><span class='qd'><b>A weak password policy</b>: password policy is an authentication concern, unrelated to memory reuse.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-051","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"hard","q":"A design places application logic and its trusted data on the same server as an internet-facing web front end, so a web compromise directly reaches the data. Which secure-architecture principle would have prevented this?","options":["Disabling TLS between tiers","Storing all tiers on one host for speed","Tiered architecture with separation of the presentation, application, and data layers","Using a single account across all tiers"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tiered architecture with separation of the presentation, application, and data layers</strong> keeps the exposed front end away from trusted data, so a web compromise does not immediately reach the database.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing all tiers on one host for speed</b>: collapsing tiers is exactly the weakness described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling TLS between tiers</b>: removing encryption weakens security and does not separate tiers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Using a single account across all tiers</b>: a shared account increases blast radius rather than separating layers.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-052","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which term describes multiple customers sharing the same underlying cloud hardware while their data remains logically isolated?","options":["Single-tenancy","On-premises hosting","Air-gapping","Multitenancy"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Multitenancy</strong> means many customers share physical infrastructure with logical isolation, a defining trait of public cloud.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Single-tenancy</b>: single-tenancy dedicates hardware to one customer, the opposite of the description.</span><span class='qd'><b>Air-gapping</b>: air-gapping physically isolates a system from networks, not a sharing model.</span><span class='qd'><b>On-premises hosting</b>: on-prem runs in the customer's own facility, not shared cloud hardware.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-053","domain":3,"obj":"3.5","diff":"medium","q":"An organization moving to the cloud fears vendor lock-in and inability to move data if the provider fails. Which architectural practice BEST mitigates this concern?","options":["Design for portability and maintain data-export/exit strategies","Encrypt nothing to ease migration","Use only proprietary provider-specific services everywhere","Delete all backups after migration"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Design for portability and maintain data-export/exit strategies</strong> reduces lock-in by keeping data and workloads movable and planning the exit up front.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt nothing to ease migration</b>: skipping encryption harms confidentiality and does not address lock-in.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use only proprietary provider-specific services everywhere</b>: heavy proprietary use worsens lock-in.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete all backups after migration</b>: deleting backups is reckless and unrelated to portability.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-054","domain":3,"obj":"3.9","diff":"medium","q":"A data center experiences intermittent equipment faults traced to electromagnetic interference and inconsistent grounding. Which facility control MOST directly addresses this?","options":["Lowering the room's lighting level","Proper electrical grounding and EMI shielding of the power and cabling infrastructure","Adding more visitor badges","Installing a taller perimeter fence"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Proper electrical grounding and EMI shielding of the power and cabling infrastructure</strong> stabilizes power quality and blocks interference that causes intermittent equipment faults.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Lowering the room's lighting level</b>: lighting has no effect on grounding or electromagnetic interference.</span><span class='qd'><b>Adding more visitor badges</b>: badging is an access control and does not address electrical faults.</span><span class='qd'><b>Installing a taller perimeter fence</b>: a fence is a boundary control unrelated to power quality or EMI.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-055","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"easy","q":"Two parties who have never met need to establish a shared secret over an untrusted network without transmitting the secret itself. Which technique BEST accomplishes this?","options":["Publishing the key on a website","Sending the AES key in plaintext email","Diffie-Hellman key exchange","Hashing a password and sharing the digest"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Diffie-Hellman key exchange</strong> lets two parties derive a shared secret over a public channel without ever transmitting the secret.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Sending the AES key in plaintext email</b>: transmitting the key exposes it to interception.</span><span class='qd'><b>Publishing the key on a website</b>: publishing a secret makes it public, defeating confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hashing a password and sharing the digest</b>: a shared digest is not a negotiated shared secret and can be replayed or cracked.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-056","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"A user wants to send a confidential message so that ONLY the intended recipient can read it, using public-key cryptography. Which key should the sender use?","options":["A shared symmetric key posted publicly","The recipient's private key","The sender's private key","The recipient's public key"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The recipient's public key</strong> encrypts the message so that only the matching recipient's private key can decrypt it, ensuring confidentiality.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The recipient's private key</b>: the sender does not possess the recipient's private key, and using it would not provide confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>The sender's private key</b>: encrypting with the sender's private key provides a signature, not confidentiality—anyone can decrypt with the public key.</span><span class='qd'><b>A shared symmetric key posted publicly</b>: a public key posted openly gives everyone the ability to decrypt.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-057","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"To provide nonrepudiation and integrity for a contract, a sender signs it. Which key does the signer use to create the digital signature?","options":["The signer's private key","The signer's public key","The recipient's public key","A random session key"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The signer's private key</strong> creates a digital signature that anyone can verify with the signer's public key, providing integrity and nonrepudiation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The signer's public key</b>: the public key verifies, not creates, a signature.</span><span class='qd'><b>The recipient's public key</b>: that key is used to encrypt for confidentiality, not to sign.</span><span class='qd'><b>A random session key</b>: a symmetric session key cannot provide nonrepudiation because it is shared.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-058","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"A protocol encrypts a bulk message with a fast symmetric cipher and then encrypts that symmetric key with the recipient's public key. Why is this hybrid approach preferred?","options":["It avoids using any keys at all","It combines symmetric speed for data with asymmetric convenience for key distribution","It makes the data impossible to decrypt even by the recipient","It replaces the need for hashing entirely"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It combines symmetric speed for data with asymmetric convenience for key distribution</strong> is why hybrid cryptography is used—symmetric handles bulk efficiently while asymmetric solves key exchange.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It avoids using any keys at all</b>: the scheme uses keys throughout; it does not eliminate them.</span><span class='qd'><b>It makes the data impossible to decrypt even by the recipient</b>: the recipient must be able to decrypt, so this is false.</span><span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for hashing entirely</b>: hashing serves integrity and is orthogonal to hybrid encryption.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-059","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"A developer must store user passwords so that even a database breach does not reveal them, while defending against precomputed rainbow tables. Which approach is BEST?","options":["Store plaintext passwords in a protected column","Encrypt passwords with a single shared symmetric key","Hash each password with a slow, salted algorithm such as bcrypt/Argon2","Base64-encode the passwords"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Hash each password with a slow, salted algorithm such as bcrypt/Argon2</strong> makes precomputation useless (unique salt) and brute force costly (slow function), the accepted password-storage practice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Store plaintext passwords in a protected column</b>: plaintext is fully exposed on any breach.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypt passwords with a single shared symmetric key</b>: a recoverable key allows mass decryption if the key leaks; hashing is preferred for verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Base64-encode the passwords</b>: Base64 is trivially reversible and offers no protection.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-060","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"easy","q":"Which property distinguishes a cryptographic hash function from encryption?","options":["A hash guarantees confidentiality of the message","A hash can always be decrypted with the right key","A hash requires a public/private key pair","A hash is one-way and cannot be reversed to recover the input"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A hash is one-way and cannot be reversed to recover the input</strong>, which is the defining property versus reversible encryption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A hash can always be decrypted with the right key</b>: hashes have no key and are not decryptable.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hash requires a public/private key pair</b>: plain hashing uses no keys.</span><span class='qd'><b>A hash guarantees confidentiality of the message</b>: hashing provides integrity, not confidentiality.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-061","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"hard","q":"A security lead must retire an internal use of MD5 for integrity checks. What is the PRIMARY reason MD5 is unacceptable for security purposes today?","options":["It is vulnerable to collision attacks, so two different inputs can share a digest","It is too slow for modern hardware","It requires a private key that is hard to manage","It produces digests that are too long to store"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>It is vulnerable to collision attacks, so two different inputs can share a digest</strong> is why MD5 is deprecated—collisions undermine integrity guarantees.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It is too slow for modern hardware</b>: MD5 is actually fast; speed is not its problem for integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>It requires a private key that is hard to manage</b>: MD5 uses no key.</span><span class='qd'><b>It produces digests that are too long to store</b>: at 128 bits, MD5 digests are short, not too long.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-062","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"easy","q":"A browser must confirm that a public key truly belongs to the website it is visiting. Which PKI component vouches for that binding by signing the certificate?","options":["The registration authority (RA)","The certificate authority (CA)","The certificate revocation list (CRL)","The relying party"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The certificate authority (CA)</strong> signs the certificate, binding a public key to an identity so relying parties can trust it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The registration authority (RA)</b>: the RA verifies identity for the CA but does not sign certificates.</span><span class='qd'><b>The certificate revocation list (CRL)</b>: a CRL lists revoked certificates; it does not vouch for the binding.</span><span class='qd'><b>The relying party</b>: the relying party consumes the certificate; it does not issue or sign it.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-063","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"An application needs to check whether a presented X.509 certificate has been revoked in near real time without downloading a large list. Which mechanism is MOST appropriate?","options":["Ignoring revocation entirely","Downloading the full CRL every request","Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP)","Using a self-signed certificate"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP)</strong> queries revocation status for a single certificate in real time, avoiding a full CRL download.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Downloading the full CRL every request</b>: repeatedly pulling a large CRL is inefficient and may be stale.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignoring revocation entirely</b>: skipping revocation checks allows use of compromised certificates.</span><span class='qd'><b>Using a self-signed certificate</b>: a self-signed cert bypasses the CA trust chain and does not solve revocation checking.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-064","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"hard","q":"A CA's root private key is the ultimate trust anchor. Which practice BEST protects it while still allowing day-to-day issuance?","options":["Keep the root online and issue all certificates directly from it","Store the root key in the application's source code","Email the root key to administrators as backup","Keep the root offline in an HSM and use subordinate/issuing CAs for daily issuance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Keep the root offline in an HSM and use subordinate/issuing CAs for daily issuance</strong> minimizes root exposure while delegating routine issuance to intermediates.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Keep the root online and issue all certificates directly from it</b>: an online root is far more exposed to compromise.</span><span class='qd'><b>Email the root key to administrators as backup</b>: emailing the root key is a catastrophic exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store the root key in the application's source code</b>: embedding keys in code leaks them to anyone with source access.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-065","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"easy","q":"Which statement correctly pairs a cryptographic goal with the mechanism that provides it?","options":["Confidentiality via encryption; integrity via hashing; nonrepudiation via digital signatures","Confidentiality via hashing; integrity via encryption; nonrepudiation via Base64","Availability via encryption; confidentiality via RAID","Integrity via load balancing; confidentiality via DNS"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Confidentiality via encryption; integrity via hashing; nonrepudiation via digital signatures</strong> correctly maps each goal to its primary mechanism.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality via hashing; integrity via encryption; nonrepudiation via Base64</b>: hashing does not provide confidentiality and Base64 provides nothing cryptographic.</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability via encryption; confidentiality via RAID</b>: encryption does not ensure availability and RAID does not provide confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>Integrity via load balancing; confidentiality via DNS</b>: neither load balancing nor DNS is a cryptographic control.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-066","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"A block cipher is used in a mode where identical plaintext blocks produce identical ciphertext blocks, revealing patterns in an image. Which mode causes this weakness?","options":["Cipher Block Chaining (CBC)","Electronic Code Book (ECB)","Counter (CTR)","Galois/Counter Mode (GCM)"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Electronic Code Book (ECB)</strong> encrypts each block independently, so identical plaintext yields identical ciphertext, leaking structure such as image outlines.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cipher Block Chaining (CBC)</b>: CBC chains blocks with an IV so identical plaintext blocks differ.</span><span class='qd'><b>Counter (CTR)</b>: CTR uses a counter/nonce so blocks are unique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Galois/Counter Mode (GCM)</b>: GCM is a counter-based authenticated mode that does not leak patterns.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-067","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"hard","q":"A design needs both confidentiality and integrity/authenticity of ciphertext in one operation, detecting any tampering. Which choice is BEST?","options":["Plain RSA encryption of the whole file","AES-ECB with no MAC","An authenticated encryption mode such as AES-GCM","SHA-256 of the plaintext only"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>An authenticated encryption mode such as AES-GCM</strong> provides confidentiality plus an integrity/authenticity tag in a single operation, detecting tampering.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>AES-ECB with no MAC</b>: ECB leaks patterns and provides no integrity check.</span><span class='qd'><b>Plain RSA encryption of the whole file</b>: RSA is impractical for bulk data and, unpadded/unauthenticated, does not provide AEAD.</span><span class='qd'><b>SHA-256 of the plaintext only</b>: a bare hash provides no confidentiality and no keyed authenticity.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-068","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants strong asymmetric security with much smaller keys and lower compute cost than RSA, ideal for mobile devices. Which algorithm family fits BEST?","options":["MD5","Triple DES","RC4","Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC)</strong> achieves equivalent security to RSA with far smaller keys and less computation, well suited to constrained mobile devices.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Triple DES</b>: 3DES is a symmetric cipher, not an asymmetric alternative to RSA, and is being retired.</span><span class='qd'><b>RC4</b>: RC4 is a broken symmetric stream cipher, not an asymmetric option.</span><span class='qd'><b>MD5</b>: MD5 is a broken hash function, not an asymmetric algorithm.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-069","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"easy","q":"A team must generate encryption keys that an attacker cannot predict. What is the MOST important property of the source used to create them?","options":["It uses a cryptographically secure random number generator with sufficient entropy","It uses the current timestamp only","It reuses the same seed for reproducibility","It derives keys from the username"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>It uses a cryptographically secure random number generator with sufficient entropy</strong> ensures keys are unpredictable, the foundation of key strength.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It uses the current timestamp only</b>: timestamps are guessable and low-entropy, producing predictable keys.</span><span class='qd'><b>It reuses the same seed for reproducibility</b>: a fixed seed makes keys reproducible by attackers too.</span><span class='qd'><b>It derives keys from the username</b>: usernames are public and low-entropy, yielding weak keys.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-070","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"hard","q":"A CISO mandates that encryption keys be rotated and that old keys be securely retired at end of life. Which key-management concept requires that a key no longer in use be rendered unrecoverable?","options":["Key escrow","Key destruction (secure zeroization)","Key exchange","Key stretching"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Key destruction (secure zeroization)</strong> renders a retired key unrecoverable so it cannot be misused after end of life.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Key escrow</b>: escrow deliberately retains a recoverable copy, the opposite of destruction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Key exchange</b>: key exchange establishes shared keys; it does not retire them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Key stretching</b>: key stretching strengthens weak keys/passwords; it is unrelated to destruction.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-071","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"A law-enforcement requirement leads an organization to keep a recoverable copy of decryption keys with a trusted third party. This practice is called:","options":["Key stretching","Perfect forward secrecy","Key escrow","Salting"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Key escrow</strong> stores a recoverable copy of keys with a trusted party so data can be decrypted under defined conditions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Perfect forward secrecy</b>: PFS ensures past sessions stay secure even if a long-term key leaks—the opposite intent of escrow.</span><span class='qd'><b>Key stretching</b>: key stretching hardens weak secrets, not a recovery mechanism.</span><span class='qd'><b>Salting</b>: salting adds randomness to hashes; it is unrelated to key recovery.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-072","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"hard","q":"A messaging app wants past conversations to remain secure even if a server's long-term private key is later compromised. Which property must its key agreement provide?","options":["Storing session keys in plaintext logs","Key escrow of every session key","Reuse of one static key for all sessions","Perfect forward secrecy (ephemeral keys per session)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Perfect forward secrecy (ephemeral keys per session)</strong> ensures that compromising a long-term key does not expose previously recorded sessions, because each used a fresh ephemeral key.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Key escrow of every session key</b>: escrowing keys makes past sessions recoverable, defeating the goal.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reuse of one static key for all sessions</b>: a static key means one compromise exposes everything.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing session keys in plaintext logs</b>: logging keys in plaintext directly exposes past sessions.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-073","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"easy","q":"Which cryptographic service does a message authentication code (HMAC) primarily provide?","options":["Data integrity and authenticity using a shared secret key","Confidentiality of the message contents","Nonrepudiation to third parties","Compression of the message"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Data integrity and authenticity using a shared secret key</strong> is what an HMAC provides—verifying the message was not altered and came from a holder of the shared key.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Confidentiality of the message contents</b>: an HMAC does not encrypt or hide content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Nonrepudiation to third parties</b>: because the key is shared, either party could produce the MAC, so it does not provide nonrepudiation; a digital signature does.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compression of the message</b>: HMAC does not compress data.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-074","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"medium","q":"An architect must select between RSA and AES for encrypting a 50 MB backup file directly. Which is correct and why?","options":["Use RSA because asymmetric ciphers are faster for large files","Use AES because symmetric ciphers are efficient for bulk data; RSA is impractical for large payloads","Use RSA to avoid key management entirely","Use AES because it uses public/private key pairs"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Use AES because symmetric ciphers are efficient for bulk data; RSA is impractical for large payloads</strong> reflects that AES handles large volumes efficiently while RSA is slow and size-limited.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Use RSA because asymmetric ciphers are faster for large files</b>: RSA is much slower than AES for bulk data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use RSA to avoid key management entirely</b>: RSA still requires key management, and it is unsuited to bulk encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use AES because it uses public/private key pairs</b>: AES is symmetric and uses a single shared key, not a key pair.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-075","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"easy","q":"A developer adds a unique random value to each password before hashing so that identical passwords produce different digests. This value is called a:","options":["Initialization vector for a block cipher","Nonce for replay protection","Salt","Certificate serial number"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Salt</strong> is a unique random value added to each password before hashing, defeating precomputed tables and making identical passwords hash differently.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Nonce for replay protection</b>: a nonce prevents replay in protocols; it is not the per-password hashing value.</span><span class='qd'><b>Initialization vector for a block cipher</b>: an IV randomizes symmetric encryption, not password hashing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificate serial number</b>: a serial number identifies a certificate, unrelated to hashing passwords.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-076","domain":3,"obj":"3.9","diff":"medium","q":"A facilities team wants early warning of a slow water leak beneath the raised floor of a data center before it reaches equipment. Which control is MOST appropriate?","options":["A larger UPS battery bank","A brighter overhead lighting array","A thicker entrance door","Water/moisture detection sensors under the raised floor tied to alerting"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Water/moisture detection sensors under the raised floor tied to alerting</strong> give early warning of leaks so staff can respond before water reaches powered equipment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A brighter overhead lighting array</b>: lighting does not detect water and is unrelated to leaks.</span><span class='qd'><b>A thicker entrance door</b>: a door addresses physical access, not sub-floor water.</span><span class='qd'><b>A larger UPS battery bank</b>: more battery capacity addresses power continuity, not leak detection.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-077","domain":3,"obj":"3.8","diff":"medium","q":"A facility wants to prevent a vehicle from ramming through the lobby entrance while still allowing pedestrians to pass. Which physical control is MOST appropriate?","options":["Bollards installed in front of the entrance","A warning banner on the front door","A stronger Wi-Fi password","A brighter lobby ceiling light"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Bollards installed in front of the entrance</strong> are sturdy posts that stop vehicle ramming while leaving pedestrian access open.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A warning banner on the front door</b>: a banner is a deterrent notice and cannot physically stop a vehicle.</span><span class='qd'><b>A stronger Wi-Fi password</b>: a Wi-Fi password is a logical control unrelated to vehicle barriers.</span><span class='qd'><b>A brighter lobby ceiling light</b>: lighting aids surveillance but does not block a vehicle.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-078","domain":3,"obj":"3.6","diff":"hard","q":"A CISO is planning for the eventual arrival of large-scale quantum computers that threaten RSA and ECC. Which strategy is MOST forward-looking?","options":["Do nothing, since quantum computers do not exist yet","Adopt crypto-agility and begin evaluating post-quantum (quantum-resistant) algorithms","Switch everything to MD5","Increase all RSA keys to 512 bits"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Adopt crypto-agility and begin evaluating post-quantum (quantum-resistant) algorithms</strong> prepares the organization to swap algorithms as standards mature, addressing the quantum threat.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Do nothing, since quantum computers do not exist yet</b>: 'harvest now, decrypt later' makes early planning prudent.</span><span class='qd'><b>Switch everything to MD5</b>: MD5 is a broken hash, not a quantum defense.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increase all RSA keys to 512 bits</b>: 512-bit RSA is already trivially broken and smaller than current keys.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-079","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"medium","q":"An attacker who has captured ciphertext systematically tries every possible key until the plaintext appears. Which cryptanalytic attack is this?","options":["Side-channel attack","Chosen-plaintext attack","Brute-force attack","Birthday attack"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Brute-force attack</strong> exhaustively tries all possible keys, which is why sufficient key length is essential.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Chosen-plaintext attack</b>: that attack requires the ability to encrypt chosen plaintexts, not exhaustive key search.</span><span class='qd'><b>Side-channel attack</b>: side-channel attacks exploit physical leakage such as timing or power, not key guessing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Birthday attack</b>: a birthday attack targets hash collisions, not key exhaustion.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-080","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"hard","q":"An adversary measures the exact time and power a smart card uses while performing decryption and deduces the private key. Which attack category is this?","options":["Meet-in-the-middle attack","Ciphertext-only attack","Known-plaintext attack","Side-channel attack"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Side-channel attack</strong> extracts secrets from physical leakage such as timing and power consumption rather than from the algorithm's math.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ciphertext-only attack</b>: that attack works from ciphertext alone, not physical measurements.</span><span class='qd'><b>Known-plaintext attack</b>: that requires known plaintext/ciphertext pairs, not power/timing data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Meet-in-the-middle attack</b>: that targets multi-stage ciphers algorithmically, not via side channels.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-081","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"medium","q":"An attacker exploits the mathematics of hash collisions, needing far fewer attempts than the full output space to find any two messages with the same digest. This is a:","options":["Birthday attack","Dictionary attack","Replay attack","Downgrade attack"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Birthday attack</strong> uses the birthday paradox so that finding any collision requires roughly the square root of the output space, far fewer attempts than brute force.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Dictionary attack</b>: a dictionary attack tries likely passwords, not hash collisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replay attack</b>: a replay attack resends captured messages, unrelated to collisions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Downgrade attack</b>: a downgrade attack forces weaker protocols, not collision finding.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-082","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"medium","q":"An attacker precomputes hashes of common passwords in large lookup tables to reverse unsalted password hashes quickly. Which attack and defense pair is correct?","options":["Man-in-the-middle; defended by longer passwords","Rainbow table attack; defended by per-password salting","Brute force; defended by Base64 encoding","Replay; defended by compression"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Rainbow table attack; defended by per-password salting</strong> is correct—unique salts make precomputed tables useless.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Man-in-the-middle; defended by longer passwords</b>: MITM intercepts communications and is unrelated to precomputed hash tables.</span><span class='qd'><b>Brute force; defended by Base64 encoding</b>: rainbow tables are precomputation, not live brute force, and Base64 is not a defense.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replay; defended by compression</b>: replay and compression have nothing to do with reversing hashes.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-083","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"hard","q":"During a TLS negotiation, an attacker forces the client and server to use an obsolete, weak cipher suite that the attacker can break. This is a:","options":["Chosen-ciphertext attack","Birthday attack","Downgrade attack","Timing attack"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Downgrade attack</strong> coerces peers into a weaker protocol or cipher that the attacker can defeat.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Birthday attack</b>: a birthday attack targets hash collisions, not protocol negotiation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Chosen-ciphertext attack</b>: that submits crafted ciphertexts for decryption, not forcing weak suites.</span><span class='qd'><b>Timing attack</b>: a timing attack measures execution time, unrelated to cipher-suite negotiation.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-084","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"easy","q":"An analyst has many plaintext/ciphertext pairs produced under the same key and uses them to deduce the key. Which classic cryptanalytic model is this?","options":["Social engineering","Ciphertext-only attack","Side-channel attack","Known-plaintext attack"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Known-plaintext attack</strong> uses matched plaintext and ciphertext pairs to recover the key or algorithm behavior.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ciphertext-only attack</b>: that has only ciphertext, not plaintext pairs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Side-channel attack</b>: that relies on physical leakage, not plaintext pairs.</span><span class='qd'><b>Social engineering</b>: social engineering manipulates people, not cryptanalysis of pairs.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-085","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"medium","q":"An attacker can submit chosen ciphertexts to a decryption oracle and observe the results to learn about the key or plaintext. This model is a:","options":["Chosen-ciphertext attack","Known-plaintext attack","Brute-force attack","Rainbow table attack"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Chosen-ciphertext attack</strong> lets the adversary pick ciphertexts and study the decryption outputs to break the scheme.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Known-plaintext attack</b>: that uses observed plaintext pairs, not chosen ciphertexts fed to an oracle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Brute-force attack</b>: brute force tries all keys and does not use a decryption oracle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rainbow table attack</b>: rainbow tables reverse hashes, not decrypt chosen ciphertexts.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-086","domain":3,"obj":"3.7","diff":"hard","q":"A double-encryption scheme uses two keys, but an attacker encrypts from one end and decrypts from the other, matching intermediate values to cut the effective work. This is a:","options":["Birthday attack","Meet-in-the-middle attack","Replay attack","Padding oracle attack"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Meet-in-the-middle attack</strong> exploits multi-stage encryption by matching intermediate results, which is why 2DES gives little benefit over DES.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Birthday attack</b>: a birthday attack finds hash collisions, not intermediate matches in double encryption.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replay attack</b>: replay resends messages and is unrelated to double-encryption analysis.</span><span class='qd'><b>Padding oracle attack</b>: a padding oracle exploits padding-validation leaks, not intermediate key matching.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-087","domain":3,"obj":"3.8","diff":"medium","q":"A campus is redesigned so that landscaping, lighting, and clear sightlines naturally discourage intruders and increase the chance they are seen. Which discipline is being applied?","options":["Data loss prevention","Business impact analysis","Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design (CPTED)","Quantitative risk analysis"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design (CPTED)</strong> uses natural surveillance, access control, and territorial reinforcement to deter crime through the built environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Business impact analysis</b>: a BIA assesses impact of disruptions, not physical deterrence design.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data loss prevention</b>: DLP is a data-protection technology, not facility design.</span><span class='qd'><b>Quantitative risk analysis</b>: that is a risk-measurement method, not an environmental design approach.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-088","domain":3,"obj":"3.8","diff":"medium","q":"A CPTED design uses low hedges, open lobbies, and unobstructed windows so legitimate occupants can readily see who is present. Which CPTED strategy is this?","options":["Cryptographic access","Target hardening with bollards","Mantrap installation","Natural surveillance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Natural surveillance</strong> maximizes visibility so intruders are easily observed, a core CPTED strategy distinct from physical hardening.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Target hardening with bollards</b>: bollards are physical barriers, not the visibility strategy described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Mantrap installation</b>: a mantrap controls entry flow; it is not about sightlines.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cryptographic access</b>: cryptography is a logical control, unrelated to CPTED sightlines.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-089","domain":3,"obj":"3.8","diff":"hard","q":"To stop tailgating at a secure entrance, a facility installs a two-door vestibule where the second door opens only after the first closes and one person is verified. This control is a:","options":["Mantrap (access control vestibule)","Turnstile with no verification","Simple propped door","Loading dock"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Mantrap (access control vestibule)</strong> uses interlocked doors to admit one verified person at a time, directly preventing tailgating.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Turnstile with no verification</b>: an unverified turnstile can still be bypassed and does not confirm identity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Simple propped door</b>: a propped door defeats access control entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Loading dock</b>: a dock is a delivery area, not an anti-tailgating vestibule.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-090","domain":3,"obj":"3.8","diff":"medium","q":"CPTED's 'territorial reinforcement' uses design cues to signal ownership of a space. Which example BEST illustrates it?","options":["A random maze of unmarked corridors","Clear signage, defined property borders, and well-maintained landscaping that signal the area is cared for and monitored","Removing all lighting to hide the building","Leaving the perimeter undefined"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Clear signage, defined property borders, and well-maintained landscaping that signal the area is cared for and monitored</strong> exemplifies territorial reinforcement, marking legitimate control of the space.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A random maze of unmarked corridors</b>: confusing layouts do not reinforce ownership cues.</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing all lighting to hide the building</b>: darkness reduces surveillance and invites crime.</span><span class='qd'><b>Leaving the perimeter undefined</b>: an undefined border removes the ownership signal territorial reinforcement relies on.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-091","domain":3,"obj":"3.8","diff":"easy","q":"Where should an organization ideally locate a data center to reduce environmental and physical risk?","options":["In a basement below the local flood line","In a ground-floor storefront with large windows facing the street","On a top floor of a windowless, non-flood-prone building away from public visibility","On an unsecured rooftop patio"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>On a top floor of a windowless, non-flood-prone building away from public visibility</strong> reduces flooding, forced-entry, and reconnaissance risks.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>In a ground-floor storefront with large windows facing the street</b>: high visibility and glass increase reconnaissance and break-in risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>In a basement below the local flood line</b>: basements below flood level risk water damage.</span><span class='qd'><b>On an unsecured rooftop patio</b>: an exposed, unsecured location invites tampering and weather exposure.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-092","domain":3,"obj":"3.8","diff":"medium","q":"An architect designs concentric layers of physical defense: fenced perimeter, guarded lobby, badge-controlled floor, and locked server cage. Which physical-security concept is this?","options":["Fail-open by default","A single strong outer wall only","Security through obscurity","Security zones / defense in depth (layered physical security)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Security zones / defense in depth (layered physical security)</strong> nests progressively stronger controls so an intruder must defeat multiple layers to reach the asset.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single strong outer wall only</b>: relying on one barrier fails once it is breached.</span><span class='qd'><b>Security through obscurity</b>: hiding the design is not the layered-zone concept described.</span><span class='qd'><b>Fail-open by default</b>: fail-open is a failure behavior, not a layered physical design.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-093","domain":3,"obj":"3.9","diff":"easy","q":"A server room must ride through brief power sags and provide time to shut down gracefully during a short outage. Which control provides this immediate, short-duration power?","options":["An uninterruptible power supply (UPS)","A diesel generator alone","A surge protector power strip","A second internet circuit"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>An uninterruptible power supply (UPS)</strong> delivers instant battery power to bridge sags and short outages and allows orderly shutdown or generator start.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A diesel generator alone</b>: generators take seconds to start, so they cannot cover the instant gap a UPS fills.</span><span class='qd'><b>A surge protector power strip</b>: a surge protector clamps spikes but supplies no ride-through power.</span><span class='qd'><b>A second internet circuit</b>: redundant internet does nothing for electrical power loss.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-094","domain":3,"obj":"3.9","diff":"hard","q":"A data center needs a fire-suppression system that will not damage electronic equipment or leave residue when discharged in an occupied room. Which is MOST appropriate?","options":["A traditional wet-pipe water sprinkler over the racks","A clean agent (inert gas) suppression system","A dry-chemical powder extinguisher flooded room-wide","No suppression, relying on smoke detectors only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A clean agent (inert gas) suppression system</strong> extinguishes fire without water damage or corrosive residue and is safer for occupied electronic spaces.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A traditional wet-pipe water sprinkler over the racks</b>: water damages powered electronics and is a last resort for server rooms.</span><span class='qd'><b>A dry-chemical powder extinguisher flooded room-wide</b>: dry chemical leaves corrosive residue harmful to equipment.</span><span class='qd'><b>No suppression, relying on smoke detectors only</b>: detection without suppression allows a fire to spread.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-095","domain":3,"obj":"3.9","diff":"medium","q":"A data center controls temperature and humidity to prevent both overheating and static discharge. Which system is responsible for this environmental control?","options":["The intrusion detection system","The building's fire alarm panel","HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning)","The badge access controller"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning)</strong> maintains proper temperature and humidity, preventing overheating and static-related damage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The building's fire alarm panel</b>: the fire panel handles detection/alarm, not climate control.</span><span class='qd'><b>The intrusion detection system</b>: an IDS detects unauthorized access, not temperature or humidity.</span><span class='qd'><b>The badge access controller</b>: badge control governs entry, not environmental conditions.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-096","domain":3,"obj":"3.9","diff":"hard","q":"A facilities engineer notes that unusually low humidity in the server room increases the risk of static discharge damaging components, while high humidity risks condensation. What is the BEST response?","options":["Raise the temperature to compensate for humidity","Set humidity as low as possible to save energy","Turn off humidity control entirely","Maintain humidity within the recommended range using HVAC humidity control"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Maintain humidity within the recommended range using HVAC humidity control</strong> balances the twin risks—too dry causes static, too humid causes condensation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Set humidity as low as possible to save energy</b>: very low humidity raises static-discharge risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Turn off humidity control entirely</b>: removing control lets humidity drift into damaging extremes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Raise the temperature to compensate for humidity</b>: higher temperature does not correct humidity and risks overheating.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-097","domain":3,"obj":"3.9","diff":"medium","q":"A data center's cooling design separates supply and return airflow so cold intake air does not mix with hot exhaust. Which layout achieves this?","options":["Hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment","Randomly facing racks in all directions","A single open room with no airflow plan","Placing all equipment against one wall"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment</strong> aligns racks so cold intake and hot exhaust are separated, improving cooling efficiency and preventing hotspots.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Randomly facing racks in all directions</b>: random orientation mixes hot and cold air, reducing cooling efficiency.</span><span class='qd'><b>A single open room with no airflow plan</b>: without an airflow plan, hot and cold air mix and create hotspots.</span><span class='qd'><b>Placing all equipment against one wall</b>: crowding equipment on one wall does not separate airflow paths.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-098","domain":3,"obj":"3.10","diff":"medium","q":"An organization is defining its information systems lifecycle and asks WHEN security requirements should first be considered. What is the BEST answer?","options":["Only after the system goes live","From the earliest requirements/initiation phase, before design begins","Only when an audit finding appears","During decommissioning only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>From the earliest requirements/initiation phase, before design begins</strong> reflects security-by-design—addressing security at the start is cheaper and more effective than retrofitting.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only after the system goes live</b>: waiting until production forces costly rework and leaves gaps.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only when an audit finding appears</b>: reacting to findings is late and piecemeal.</span><span class='qd'><b>During decommissioning only</b>: security must span the whole lifecycle, not just retirement.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-099","domain":3,"obj":"3.10","diff":"hard","q":"A system is being retired and its storage arrays held classified data. What is the MOST important security activity during this disposal phase of the lifecycle?","options":["Selling the drives on an auction site as-is","Simply unplugging the servers and discarding them","Secure media sanitization/destruction and documented data disposition","Leaving the data in place for convenience"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Secure media sanitization/destruction and documented data disposition</strong> ensures classified data cannot be recovered from retired media, the key disposal-phase control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Simply unplugging the servers and discarding them</b>: discarding intact media leaves recoverable data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Selling the drives on an auction site as-is</b>: selling unsanitized drives directly exposes classified data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Leaving the data in place for convenience</b>: retaining data on retired systems increases breach risk with no control.</span>"},
  {"id":"D3-100","domain":3,"obj":"3.10","diff":"easy","q":"Embedding security checkpoints and reviews at each phase of the system development lifecycle rather than testing only at the end is BEST described as:","options":["Testing security only during disposal","Deferring all security to post-deployment","Skipping security to speed delivery","Building security in throughout the SDLC ('shift left')"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Building security in throughout the SDLC ('shift left')</strong> integrates security activities at every phase, catching issues earlier and reducing cost and risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Deferring all security to post-deployment</b>: late security testing misses design flaws and is costly to fix.</span><span class='qd'><b>Skipping security to speed delivery</b>: omitting security trades short-term speed for major risk.</span><span class='qd'><b>Testing security only during disposal</b>: disposal is far too late to influence design and build quality.</span>"}
);
